                            <comment id="21110" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 29 Nov 2006 01:49:43 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This has fortunately already been fixed in Spring 2.0 as well as the to-be-released 1.2.9. We still throw the combined property access exceptions there, but full details are now given in its &quot;toString()&quot; implementation.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The problem only arises if some standard JDK exception wraps the outermost exception, as far as we found out: The standard JDK exception chaining never calls a nested exception&apos;s &quot;getMessage()&quot; or &quot;printStackTrace()&quot;, hence all the relevant information needs to be put into &quot;toString()&quot; there.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;FYI, 1.2.9 is planned for release in December, with an early access snapshot to be released this week. Feel free to give it a try once it is available...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
